<section class="card">
  <h2>What Redwing Is Best For</h2>

  <p>
    Redwing is best for gardeners who want red onions with better storage potential than many fresh-use red types.
  </p>

  <p>
    It still needs enough season to size and cure. If started late, it may make useful bulbs but not the storage crop you hoped for.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Is Redwing Good for Short Seasons?</h2>

  <p>
    Onions can work in short seasons, but they depend on getting an early start and matching the variety to your day length.
  </p>

  <p>
    The growing season is split between leaf growth and bulb formation. Weak early growth usually means smaller bulbs later.
  </p>

  <p>
    For short-season gardeners, transplants or well-grown starts are usually more realistic than seeding directly in the garden.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>When to Plant Redwing</h2>

  <p>
    Start onions indoors early or plant transplants as soon as conditions are workable. Onions tolerate cool weather, but young plants still need light and steady growth.
  </p>

  <p>
    Choose the right day-length type for your region. Long-day onions are typically used in northern gardens, while other regions may need different types.
  </p>

  <p>
    For local timing, use the <a href="https://growbydate.com/crops/onions/">onion growing guide</a> and your frost dates. Onion timing depends on both early growth and the bulbing window.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>How to Grow Redwing</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Start early:</strong> Onions need time to build leaves before bulbs size up.</li>
    <li><strong>Match day length:</strong> The wrong day-length type may not bulb properly.</li>
    <li><strong>Keep weeds down:</strong> Onions compete poorly with weeds because their leaves are narrow.</li>
    <li><strong>Water consistently:</strong> Steady moisture helps bulb development.</li>
    <li><strong>Feed during leaf growth:</strong> Good early growth supports larger bulbs later.</li>
    <li><strong>Stop pushing late:</strong> As tops fall and bulbs mature, storage onions need to finish and cure.</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Harvest and Storage</h2>

  <p>
    Harvest onions when the tops begin to fall and bulbs have sized properly. Let the crop mature, but do not leave bulbs in wet soil too long.
  </p>

  <p>
    Cure storage onions in a dry, airy place until necks are tight and outer skins are papery. Good curing is as important as variety choice for storage.
  </p>

  <p>
    Use thick-necked, damaged, or poorly cured bulbs first. Save the firmest, best-cured bulbs for longer storage.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Common Mistakes When Growing Redwing</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Starting too late:</strong> Late starts often make small bulbs.</li>
    <li><strong>Ignoring day length:</strong> A good onion variety still has to match your latitude.</li>
    <li><strong>Letting weeds compete:</strong> Weeds can reduce bulb size quickly.</li>
    <li><strong>Overwatering near maturity:</strong> Wet conditions can hurt curing and storage.</li>
    <li><strong>Skipping proper curing:</strong> Storage onions need dry necks and skins before long keeping.</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Redwing vs Other Onion Varieties</h2>

  <p>
    Compared with other onion varieties, Redwing should be judged by storage ability, bulb color, maturity time, and day-length fit. A great storage onion is only useful if it matches your region and has time to cure.
  </p>

  <p>
    For this crop, the better choice depends on what you want from the harvest. Redwing is worth growing when its maturity window, plant habit, and kitchen use match your garden better than a faster, larger, or more specialized alternative.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Who Should Grow Redwing?</h2>

  <p>
    Redwing is a good choice if you want onions for cooking and storage and can give the crop an early, clean start.
  </p>

  <p>
    It is less forgiving if weeds take over, starts are late, or the variety does not match your day-length zone.
  </p>
</section>

